  "referred_to_by": [
    {
      "type": "LinguisticObject",
      "content": "A **working scale model of a parabolic solar concentrator coupled to a steam piston mechanism**, manufactured in Paris in 1879 by instrument maker A. Salleron, based on the solar engine technology developed by Augustin Mouchot (1825–1912). The device consists of a silvered parabolic dish (~48 cm diameter) on a mahogany base. A blackened copper boiler is positioned at the focal point; tilting and rotating the dish tracks the sun and concentrates radiation on the boiler. Steam from the heated water drives a piston coupled to a set of wheels, demonstrating the complete conversion of solar radiation into mechanical motion. The museum likely acquired it in 1879 in direct response to the gold-medal demonstration by Mouchot and his assistant Abel Pifre at the **1878 Exposition Universelle in Paris**. This is one of the earliest solar-to-mechanical energy conversion devices in any museum collection worldwide. A comparable model exists in the Musée des Arts et Métiers, Paris (acquired 1880).",
